│ An analysis of the bug report indicates that the `dfa-jump-threading` pass is processing a chain of dependent `select` instructions in an incorrect order. The pass uses a         │
│ `SmallVector` as a LIFO stack for its worklist. When discovering `select` instructions by traversing from a user (a `switch` instruction) up the use-def chain, it finds the user  │
│ `select` first, then its operand `select`. Due to the LIFO order, it processes the operand `select` first.                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ The `unfold` logic replaces the `select` with branching, but it is not designed to update other `select` instructions that are also on the worklist. Consequently, when it         │
│ attempts to delete the operand `select`, the user `select` still holds a reference to it, triggering the assertion `SI->use_empty()`.                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ To resolve this, the processing order must be reversed to ensure that user `select` instructions are unfolded before their operand `select` instructions. This can be achieved by  │
│ changing the worklist from a LIFO stack to a FIFO queue. I will replace the `SmallVector` with a `std::deque` to implement this queue, ensuring that `select` instructions are     │
│ processed in the order they are discovered.                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ I will now apply this change.                                                                                                                                                      │
